Since we expect that variables are decorrelated in the weighted distribution, we denote W‚ä• as the subset of W in which X are mutually independent in the weighted distribution PÀúw.
Under the inÔ¨Ånite-sample setting, it is proved that if conducting weighted least squares using the weighting function in W‚ä•, almost surely there will be non-zero coefÔ¨Åcients only on stable variables, no matter whether the data generation function is linear or nonlinear (Xu et al. 2022). However, the condition for this to hold is too strict and ideal. Under the Ô¨Ånite-sample setting, we can hardly learn the sample weights corresponding to the weighting function in W‚ä•.
We now take a look at two speciÔ¨Åc techniques of sample reweighting, which will be incorporated into our algorithms.

DWR (Kuang et al. 2020) aims to remove linear correlations between each two variables, i.e.,

wÀÜ(X) = arg min

