A.2 Training Details
We generate X = {S, V } from a multivariate Gaussian distribution X ‚àº N (0, Œ£). In this way, we can simulate different correlation structures of X through the control of covariance matrix Œ£. In our experiments, we tend to make the correlations inside stable variables strong. For simplicity,
We further set Œ£ = Diag Œ£(S), Œ£(V ) , assuming block
structure. For Œ£(S) ‚àà Rps√óps , its elements are: Œ£(jSk) = œÅs for j = k and Œ£(jSk) = 1 for j = k. For Œ£(V ) ‚àà Rpv√ópv , its elements are: Œ£(jVk ) = œÅv for j = k and Œ£(jVk ) = 1 for j = k. Despite we can simulate more complex settings by manipulating the covariance matrix Œ£, such a simpliÔ¨Åed setting is

enough since it can adjust correlation inside S or inside V . In our experiments, to simulate the scenario where correlations inside stable variables are strong, we tend to set œÅs a large value. We set œÅs = 0.9 and œÅv = 0.1 in our experiments.
For linear and nonlinear settings, we employ different data generation functions. It is worth noting that a certain degree of model misspeciÔ¨Åcation is needed, otherwise the model will be able to directly learn the true stable variables using simply OLS or MLP.
For the linear setting, we introduce the model misspeciÔ¨Åcation error by adding an extra polynomial term to the dominated linear term, and later use a linear model to Ô¨Åt the data. The generation function is as follows:

Y = f (S) + = [S, V ] ¬∑ [Œ≤s, Œ≤v]T + S¬∑,1S¬∑,2S¬∑,3 + (16)

where Œ≤s

